'The main thing I'm trying to do is come up with an effective treatment,' he said.

Crosley especially hopes to find better drugs for patients than many now which are 'highly toxic'

He's now doing course work in biochemistry and oncology and has secured a $60,000 grant to continue researching.

A promising drug developed by the University of Illinois is among the compounds he's currently testing.

The drug, Pac-1, has shown some results with lymphoma, which carries a mortality rate of 85 per cent.

He's also hoping to find something easier for patients to process.

'Many of the drugs are highly toxic,' he told reporters.

In Sladjana's case, the fatal problem came from internal bleeding cause by a medication.

She was initially diagnosed in 1996.

Despite undergoing six major surgeries and multiple clinical trials, the cancer metastasized to her liver and lungs.

